Claims We claim: 1 . A connected and automated vehicle highway (CAVH) system comprising sensing, communication, and control components connected through segments and nodes that manage an entire transportation system 2. The system of claim 1, wherein vehicles managed within said CAVH system comprise CAVH vehicles and non- CAVH vehicles. 3. The system of claim 1, wherein said CAVH vehicles and non-CAVH vehicles comprise manual vehicles, automated vehicles, and connected vehicles 4. The system of claim 1, wherein said segments and nodes have overlapping sensing and control areas with neighboring segment and nodes to handoff CAVH vehicles between neighboring segments and nodes. 5. The system of claim 1, wherein said CAVH system comprises four control levels: a) vehicle; b) road side unit (RSU); c) traffic control unit (TCU); and d) traffic control center (TCC) 6. The system of claim 5, wherein said vehicle control level comprises vehicles having on on-board system or application to operate a vehicle dynamic system to achieve on-road coordinate commands from an RSU. 7. The system of claim 5, wherein said RSU level involves segments or nodes managed by an RSU responsible for the sensing and control of vehicles. 8 The system of claim 7, wherein said sensing comprising information from LiDAR, computer vision, and/or radar sensors that are deployed to fully capture information in a segment or node. 9. The system of claim 8, wherein said RSU, in response to said sensing, manages collision avoidance, routing execution, lane change coordination, and high- resolution guidance commands in terms of on-road coordinates for vehicles to execute their automated driving. 10. The system of claim 5, wherein said TCU level involves multiple RSUs manages by a TCU. 1 1. The system of claim 10, wherein said TCU is responsible for updating a dynamic map of moving objects and coordinated control among RSUs for continuous automated driving. 12. The system of claim 10, wherein multiple TCUs are connected through TCCs to cover a region or subnetwork. 13. The system of claim 5, wherein said TCC level comprises high- performance computing and cloud services responsible for managing overall routing plans and updating a dynamic map of congestion, incidents, inclement weather, and events with regional impact. 14 The system of claim 13, wherein said TCC level is further responsible for managing connecting with other application services comprising: payment and transaction systems, regional traffic management centers (TMCs), and third-party applications. 1 5. The system of claim 13, comprising multiple TCCs to facilitate CAVH driving between or across large metropolitan areas. 16. The system of claim 1 , wherein said sensing, communication, and control components comprise vehicle-level data and communication, comprising a vehicle layer comprising a vehicle-based on-board unit (OBU) layer that employs one or more or each of the following data flows: a) RSU identification and on-road guidance coordinates, wherein vehicles receive a security certificate and identification of the RSU in control and on-road guidance coordinates and other signals or notifications from the RSU in control; b) OBU sensor data comprising vehicle-based sensor data of surrounding vehicles and road conditions, wherein data is transmitted to an OBU controller to determine vehicle dynamic control signals and wherein part of the sensor data that impacts on other CAVH vehicles within the RSU is transmitted back to the RSU; and c) vehicle dynamic control signals, including gas pedal actuator, brake actuator levels, and turning angles, are generated by an OBU controller, wherein information is transmitted with wired or wireless connection to a vehicle mechanical system. 17. The system of claim 1, wherein said sensing, communication, and control components comprise an RSU layer that employs one or more or each of the following data flows: a) a vehicle identification and routing plan wherein an RSU receives an identification and high-level routing plan and coordinates signals from a TCU; b) high-resolution sensor data of moving objects and infrastructure states within the RSU coverage area are processed internally, said sensor data comprising data that may impact decision-making of an OBU controller, comprising: speed limit, traffic control device states, vehicle conflict information, weather, and road surface conditions; wherein said sensor data is transmitted to a vehicle layer and wherein sensor data that may have impact on CAVH control of a local or regional network is transmitted through wired or wireless connection to a TCU; 

 c) the RSU uses a real-time site map within a coverage area and a route execution plan of participating CA VH vehicles to generate high-resolution on-road guidance coordinates for each CAVH vehicle, wherein the guidance coordinates are transmitted to individual CAVH vehicles by wireless communication; and d) the RSU sends and receives vehicle handoff data in terms of vehicle identification, routing, and on-road guidance coordinates data to and from neighboring RSUs. 18. The system of claim 17, wherein said high-resolution on-road guidance coordinates are broadcast to all CAVH vehicles or sent through a secured dedicated communication with individual vehicles. 19. The system of claim l, wherein said sensing, communication, and control components comprise a TCU layer that employs one or more or each of the following data flows: a) CAVH vehicle identification, routing plan, and regional incidents and event alert data are received from TCCs; b) TCUs coordinate movements among RSUs in terms of pre-routing for mandatory lane changes and compliance with mandatory' lane regulations, or pre-merging due to congestion; wherein vehicle-specific coordination signals are transmitted to RSUs; c) TCUs receive sensing data from RSUs that may impact multiple CAVH roadway segments and nodes; and d) TCUs send and receive vehicle handoff data in terms of vehicle identificati on and routing data to and from neighboring TCUs. 20. The system of claim 1 , wherein said sensing, communication, and control components comprise a TCC layer that employs one or more or each of the following data flows for executing regional routing, updating regional event map, coordinating among TCUs and connecting with other applications and services: a) data exchange with transaction, payment, transit, and third party' applications; 

 b) signals comprising congestion mitigation information and active traffic management signals activated at regional or corridor levels are sent to individual TCUs; c) data exchange with regional traffic management centers regarding congestion, incidents, constructions, special events, and others traffic management information; and d) CAVH vehicle identification and high-level origin-destination and routing plan of participating vehicles. 21. The system of claim 1, wherein said sensing, communication, and control components manage system access and egress. 22. The system of claim 21, wherein CAVH vehicles are collected from key entry nodes such as parking lots, side streets, ramps, and intersections. 23. The system of claim 22, wherein upon entering the system, vehicle identification and origin-destination information is collected and transferred throughout a CAVH roadway system. 24. The system of claim 22, wherein upon exiting the system, control of CAVH vehicles is returned to drivers. 25. The system of claim 24, wherein if drivers are not immediately available, vehicles are parked at a storage/buffer location. 26. The system of claim 24, wherein if an existing node is an automated parking location, vehicles will exit the CAVH control system upon fully parked at destinations. 27. The system of claim 1 , comprising a basic segment subsystem, comprising one or more or each of the components: a basic segment and infrastructure; basic services; basic management; a vehicle and onboard subsystem; a roadside sensing and 

 command subsystem; local and regional traffic control (TCU/TCC); communication; cloud; and analytical, optimization, computing, and security centers. 28 The system of claim 27, wherein said basic segment and infrastructure component provides supporting functions to other modules, generates a high density (HD) map, provides HD positioning ability, and handles a switching function based on coverage information of different module segments. 29. The system of claim 27, wherein said vehicle and onboard system component controls and coordinates vehicles in CAVH system with the help of following modules: a) an interface module for communication between the vehicle and a human user; b) a communication module that transmits and receives vehicle control signals and traffic data to and from an RSU; c) a sensing module that, using sensors installed on vehicles, collects surrounding information and uses the information for driving decision making and sends selected information to an RSU using the communication module; d) an identification and security module that provides a vehicleâs unique information to the system for tracking and security purposes; e) a bi-level driving signal combination modules that combines information from an RSU and from a vehicleâs sensing module and divides the information into a high- level signal group and a low-level signal group; and f) an operation module that makes decisions about vehicle routing and operates the system based on a fused driving signal from other modules. 30. The system of claim 29, wherein said high-level signals comprise: lane choice, approach, route, and vehicle relative positions. 31 The system of claim 29, wherein said low-level signals comprise global position and current vehicle state. 32. The system of claim 27, wherein said roadside sensing and command subsystem component senses a roadside environment and controls or coordinates vehicles in CAVH system employing the one or more or each of the following components: a) a sensmg component that collects environmental information; b) a communication component that transmits and receives vehicle control signals and traffic data to and from a vehicle and exchanges information with an upstream TCU; and c) a control and coordination component wherein an RSU receives feedback about control and coordination commands from a TCU and passes the commands to a vehicle subsystem. 33. The system of claim 32, wherein the sensing component comprises information from LiDAR or radar sensors and from computer vision. 34. The system of claim 27, wherein said local and regional traffic control (TCU/TCC) component optimizes and controls vehicles in a CAVH system based on three levels: a) low-level (T2V) comprising driving queue management, entering/exiting, and transition; b) mid-level comprising load balancing and event alerts; and c) high-level (TMC) comprising congestion detection, alert, and mitigation. 35. The system of claim 27, wherein said cloud and CAVH service provision component provides services comprising mobility provision services, data services, application services, and interaction with other urban services and applications. 36. The system of claim 35, wherein said mobility provision services allow the CAVH system to work with other mobility provision services to improve performance. 37. The system of claim 36, wherein the other mobility provision services provide their data and information to a CAVFI cloud and receive aggregated feedback information. 38. The system of claim 35, wherein said data services help the CAVH system store data and provide an ability to process and fuse data online and offline. 39. The system of claim 35, wherein said application services provide interfaces to other services outside of the CAVH svstem. 40. The system of claim 39, wherein said interfaces include well organized and designed information for specific demands comprising park-and-nde, transit transferring events and activities, and POl (point of interest) information at destinations. 41. The system of claim 35, wherein said interaction with other urban services/applications services interacts with government agencies and commercial companies to retrieve data for robustness and accuracy. 42. The system of claim 27, wherein said analytic, optimization, computing, and security centers component hosts physical hardware and equipment required for providing CAVH sendees. 43. The system of claim 1, comprising a botleneck segment subsystem that addresses recurrent or nonrecurrent traffic congestion with relatively low speed and high density vehicles to facilitate low speed car following, driver comfort, and energy efficiency, comprising one or more or each of the components; a) a vehicle and onboard component that operates a CAVH vehicle in congested driving mode instead of regular mode to reduce fuel consumptions and increase safety and driver comfort in a microscopic level with eco-driving/platoonirig algorithms; 

 b) a roadside component that considers all traffic in a bottleneck segment and organizes CAVH vehicles to reduce shockwaves and stop-and-go waves in rnacroscopic/mesoscopic levels by speed harmonization and dynamic merge control; c) a TCC component that processes regional traffic control signals including detouring, temporary lane regulation, and interaction with other segmentsâ subsystem; d) a cloud component that, m a congested segment, uses personal data management including destination change, detouring demand, appointment reschedule, emergency, and toll collection plan; e) a sensing component that, in a bottleneck segment, requires additional sensing methods for vehicles overlapping with one another m crowded traffic that leads to line of sight issues for traffic sensors; and f) a communication component that provides extra communication capacity and devices to solve signal loss and lag. 44. The system of claim 1, comprising a merge, diverge, and weaving segment subsystem comprising multi-vehicle type control and mixed traffic control components. 45. The system of claim 44, w ierein said merge, diverge, and weaving segment subsystem provides coverage on freeways including mainline link, on-ramp, and off-ramp. 46. The system of claim 44, wherein said merge, diverge, and weaving segment subsystem manages three different types of vehicles: a) mainline thru-vehicles. b) on-ramp merging vehicles, and c) mainline diverging vehicles. 47. The system of claim 44, wdierem said merge, diverge, and weaving segment subsystem permits customized control or guidance signals to different mixes of participating vehicles equipped with or without different CAV technologies. 48. The system of claim 44, comprising a merge control system that comprises three control targets: a) vehicle control comprises vehicle identification, vehicle target iink/lane (thru, merge, diverge, thru inner lane), vehicle trajectory detection and transmission, merge control signal delivery, and human-machine interface; b) RSU control comprises a dynamic map of merging and participating vehicles, vehicle data management, optimal gap and lane changing control, vehicle data feedback, and vehicle-based control guidance signal generation; and c) TCC control comprising implementation of macroscopic merge control commands in response to macroscopic traffic conditions, including variable speed limits. 49. The system of claim 1, comprising a first and last nule subsystem that manages trip start/end driving including vehicle access/egress, driving navigation, human-machine interaction, and transition alerting and parking. 50. The system of claim 49, wherein the first and last mile subsystem comprises an access subsystem and an egress subsystem. 51. The system of claim 50, wherein said access subsystem manages and supports vehicles entering a CAVH roadway system from key nodes such as parking lots, side streets, ramps, intersections, and storage/buffer locations. 52 The system of claim 51, wherein vehicle identification and origin- destination information is collected and transferred throughout the CAVH roadway system, comprising: a) an OBU for the access system has additional functions of human-machine interaction, starting alerting, first mile navigation, and transfer-compliant driving; b) an RSU for the access system identifies accessing vehicles, collects accessing information, and charges a parking fee; 

