 d) cloud for the dismiss system gives point-of-interest (POJ) recommendations and parking information. 58. The system of claim 1 , comprising a buffer subsystem that manages parking and traveling when drivers make no response to border-approaching warnings at a CAVH boundary region. 59. The system of claim 58, wherein said buffer subsystem comprises management of buffer parking, temporary parking within CAVH coverage, and buffer loop on-road and shoulder parking. 60. The system of claim 59, wherein said buffer parking system automatically selects a buffer parking lot near a destination and executes parking when there is non response from a driver during an egress process. 61. The system of claim 60, wherein the buffer parking lot is located at a boundary area of the CAVH system. 62. The system of claim 60, wherein, when there is no buffer parking lot available near a selected destination, the buffer subsystem selects a temporary' parking lot within the CAVH system near a destination to park the vehicle, waiting for the driver to take over control. 63. The system of claim 62, wherein, when the buffer parking lot and temporary' parking lot both are not available near an egress node, the buffer system plans a buffer loop and controls a CAV vehicle on a CAVH road until the driver takes control the vehicle. 64 The system of claim 60, wherein, in areas where traffic is not busy, or under emergency situations, CAVs are permitted to park on a road shoulder. 65. The system of claim 1 , comprising an intersection subsystem that manages intersection nodes, OBUs, RSUs, TCU/TCCs, intersection services, and traffic management at intersections. 66. The system of claim 65, wherein the intersection nodes have space management and reservation to handle traffic interaction 67. The system of claim 65, comprising a mixed controller that integrates information and gives feedback between CAVH and non-CAVH vehicles. 68. The system of claim 65, wherein: a) an QBU contains vehicle dynamic control and intersection approach/departure applications m an intersection segment; b) an RSU provides vehicle lane group control and vehicle driving reservation and planning to help CAVs cross the intersection; c) TCUs/TCCs deal with approach management, RSU control, and vehicle movement management; and d) a computing and management center manages signal timing plan, lane and route management, and tracking and predicting of CAVH and non-CAVH vehicle movement and interactions. 69. The system of claim 65, wherein said intersection sendee manages vehicle grouping, lane and route execution, and pedestrian and bicycle interaction. 70. The system of claim 1, comprising a bridge, tunnel, and toll plaza subsystem that manages route planning, pre-merging control, and special lane navigation and control. 71. The system of claim 70, wherein the special lane is a high-occupancy toll lane (HOT), high-occupancy vehicle lane (HOY), or reversible lane. 72 The system of claim 70, wherein said bridge, tunnel, and toll plaza subsystem plans routes for vehicles once they enter a covered area per their: a) destination, said destinations comprising thru- traffic, going off-ramp, need to be weighed, and entering dedicated lane; and b) vehicle type, said vehicle type comprising high- occupancy vehicle, priority vehicle, and vehicle with e-toll tag. 73. The system of claim 70, wherein: a) a vehicle level manages pre-merging control signals to prepare vehicles while approaching the bridge, tunnels, or toll plaza infrastructures; b) an RSU level maintains a real-time map of participating and surrounding vehicles and generates and distributes pre-merging plans; c) a TCU level communicates with nearby control units to adjust traffic light signals and other control objectives to coordinate entrance/exit traffic and achieve a system-wade optimization; and d) a TCC level receives event signals including heavy congestion, incidents, maintenance, and extreme weather and influences control of the subsystem. 74. The system of claim 70, wherein for special lane navigation and control: a) the CAVH system determines vehicle ID and whether or not the vehicle type is eligible for special lanes; b) vehicle platoon management is provided to facilitate cooperative car-following control and enable vehicle-platoon formation; c) RSUs manage vehicle platoon formation, deformation, and inserting and leaving events; and d) TCCs/TCUs process event information signals to provide warnings and guidance signals. 75. The system of claim 74, wherein a determination of special lane eligibility considers occupancy levels for a HOV lane, electronic toll tag availability for a HOT lane, and routing plans for a reversible lane. 76. The system of claim 1, comprising a parking subsystem that manages CAV parking processes for making vehicle access and egress the CAVH system safe and efficient. 77. The system of claim 76, wherein the parking subsystem comprises three subsystems: a before trip system, a during trip system, and an after trip system. 78. The system of claim 77, wherein the before trip system comprises a human-machine interface that allows drivers to make driving requests, and selects trip origin/destination (OD). 79. The system of claim 78, wherein TCUs and TCCs compute requests and give commandments to parking lot RSUs and wherein the parking lot RSUs execute a parking lot exit control and give travel route guidance to the vehicle. 80. The system of claim 77, wherein the during trip system executes travel route and travel under the control of the whole CAVH roadway system and wherein when vehicles approach a destination, an alert is sent by an RSU to a human-machine interface onboard a vehicle to select destination parking plans. 81. The system of claim 80, wherein if the selected parking destination is beyond the CAVH system, a first and last mile system take over controls. 82. The system of claim 80, wherein if a parking destination is within a CAVH area, vehicles exit the CAVH control system upon fully parked at selected parking lots. 83. The system of claim 80, wherein if drivers are not immediately available to make parking decisions, vehicles are parked at a storage or buffer location. 84. The system of claim 77, wherein said after trip system executes parking charging and controls vehicle restarting and rerouting. 85. The system of claim 1, comprising a multi-modal terminals component that provides I2X and V2X integration with other segments and nodes. 86. The system of claim 85, comprising a multi-modal terminal segment having modes information comprising types, schedules, capacity, and routes, and provides park and ride options, pickup and drop-off locations, and gate and waiting areas. 87. The system of claim 85, comprising a vehicle and onboard system that comprising functions of navigation and self-driving within a terminal and the guided and automated parking; multimodal notification, schedule selection, adhesion; and can auto navigate to a next trip. 88. The system of claim 85, comprising a roadside sensing unit that provides within-terminal facility traffic sensing system, parking sensing, and auto parking guidance. 89. The system of claim 85, comprising local and regional traffic control, wherein TCUs/TCCs that manage intersections deal with terminal approaching and departure management, in-terminal RSU control, and an ICM (integrated corridor management) application. 90. The system of claim 85, comprising a cloud component that provides multi-model planning, mode transferring and ticketing, parking space reservation, and fare payment system. 91. The system of claim 85, comprising a multi-modal sendees component that manages multi-modal trips, parking planning, and operations. 92. The system of claim 85, comprising a management center that manages multi-modal optimization and computing, inter-system coordination, pickup and drop-off optimization, and vehicle relocation optimization. 93. A method comprising using any of the systems of claims 1 to 92 to manage connected automated vehicles.
